Today we will hear ideas about how some of those fixes to the regulation should look.  Witnesses will inform Congress how federal water regulations affect them and what they need from the government to continue operating effectively. I look forward to a knowledgeable discussion.

I applaud the Admin for heeding the calls of Americans. A revision to the rule is desperately needed to provide greater clarity to states. Instead of rushing forward with burdensome federal regulations, the gov needs to do its due diligence & propose a rule that is helpful.

The shortcomings of WOTUS are so self-evident that it is not surprising this onerous rule has been challenged across the country. And now we can point to a very encouraging action from the new admin: @POTUS recently issued an executive order to review the WOTUS rule.

Our nation depends on the hard work of farmers & ranchers: these men and women simply don’t have the time to deal with bureaucratic nonsense. Of course, it’s not just them who suffer:costly & unnecessary government mandates have drastic economic impacts on each & every one of us.

For example, when WOTUS was proposed there was a large outcry from stakeholders across the nation that the rule’s vague definitions regarding navigable water could include sometimes-dry drainage ditches on private farmland.  It is absurd to consider a dry ditch “navigable.”

We all want to be good stewards of the environment.  We also want to be good stewards for the people we represent.  When a federal agency overlooks the needs of U.S. citizens, we in Congress have a duty to ask questions & address the concerns of our constituents. @HouseScience

I am very pleased to have representatives here today from my home state of Arizona to discuss how this rule would affect them and what changes they believe would make water regulations better for this country.

WOTUS rule amounted to one of the biggest federal overreaches in modern history.  The rule’s flimsy definitions & underlying science means that the EPA had the ability to regulate private land & also placed significant financial burdens on some of our country’s hardest workers.

OPENING STATEMENT FOR @HouseScience subcommittee hearing: Welcome to today’s hearing, “The Future of WOTUS: Examining the Role of States.”  I want to thank our expert panel of witnesses for being here today and agreeing to testify about this important topic.

The #WOTUS rule imposed by Obama admin crippled states’ ability to regulate bodies of water. States should have this power, not Washington bureaucrats. Learn how @HouseScience is working to improve future federal water rules: https://science.house.gov/legislation/hearings/subcommittee-environment-hearing-future-wotus-examining-role-states …pic.twitter.com/P1F8td4xbQ

ICYMI - my opening statement for today's joint @HouseScience subcommittee hearing on geoengineering: https://biggs.house.gov/media/press-releases/congressman-andy-biggs-opening-statement-joint-subcommittee-hearing-0 … #AZ05
Again, I want to thank the witnesses for being here today, and I look forward to hearing more about these interesting concepts.
The purpose of this hearing is to discuss the viability of geoengineering and any early-stage research associated with this approach.
We have a responsibility to explore these concepts, learn as much as possible & discuss ideas to help support research.
Today, we will learn about what research has been conducted on geoengineering and which promising concepts should be explored further.
Since concepts involved are still so new, we cannot say definitively if geoengineering tech warrants full-scale development or deployment.
While there are at least a few programs in our nation’s universities looking into these concepts, federal research is still limited.
Avenues of geoengineering research & others are still in the developmental stage & any or all of them may warrant further exploration.
Geoengineering is the concept of using scientific understanding to alter the atmosphere in a way that produces positive outcomes & results.
Since this is the first time we are discussing geoengineering this Congress, it is important to explain what geoengineering actually is.

TODAY: @HouseScience assesses the status of geoengineering research, tech & innovation in the U.S. https://science.house.gov/legislation/hearings/subcommittee-environment-and-subcommittee-energy-hearing-geoengineering … #AZ05pic.twitter.com/cdyDsx5rY0

When the free market operates, innovation breaks through and the economy thrives.
The sooner this type of research comes to fruition and can be commercialized by the private sector, the better.

I am encouraged research is underway to improve our ability to generate biofuels more efficiently, from traditional sources & new sources.
Furthermore, the federal government’s biofuel policies have had an unintended adverse effect on food costs.
By continuing to force technologies into the market that are not competitive or in demand, we are doing the American people a disservice.
“FUEL” in title is an acronym that stands for “farewell to unnecessary energy lifelines.” I hope America will follow that policy directive.
I will be introducing the FUEL Reform Act tomorrow to fully eliminate the biofuel subsidies & related programs in title IX of the farm bill.
Rather than spending taxpayer $ on misguided subsidies & inefficient commercial scale projects, we should avoid intervening in free market.
These federal policies prop up mediocre business ventures, limit opportunities for business ideas & stifle innovation in the private sector.

ICYMI: My opening statement for today's @HouseScience subcommittee hearing to examine the social cost of carbon:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SsyEQN9OWhc …
I look forward to working with the @realDonaldTrump administration to renew faith in American ingenuity and technological development.
America’s strength emanates from our resilience & flexibility.  Attempts to justify gov regs over industry innovations hinders growth.
The SCC is nothing but a one-sided manipulation of parameters to fit policy-driven agendas of the previous of the previous administration.
The previous administration disregarded scientific integrity by overestimating climate change resulting from greenhouse gas emissions.
It is simply not right for Americans to be bearing the brunt of costs when the majority of benefits will be conferred away from home.
As we will learn today, the SCC working group ignored two major OMB recommendations for federal agency rulemaking. @HouseScience
Energy is the bedrock of our society. @HouseScience
Today we will examine the previous administration’s determination of the Social Cost of Carbon & explore why the calculated value is flawed.pic.twitter.com/iyoMfgDakf
